In order to be ''positively-selected'', thymocytes will have to interact with several cell surface molecules, [[MHC]], to ensure reactivity and specificity.<ref name="jimmunol.org">Baldwin TA, Hogquist KA, Jameson SC, The fourth way? Harnessing aggressive tendencies in the thymus. “J Immunol.” 173:6515-20, 2004. [http://www.jimmunol.org/cgi/content/full/173/11/6515]</ref> 

Positive selection selects cells with a [[T cell receptor]] able to bind [[Major histocompatibility complex|MHC]] class I or II molecules with at least a weak affinity. This eliminates (by a process called "death by neglect") those T cells which would be non-functional due to an inability to bind MHC.
|| 
Negative selection is the active induction of apoptosis in thymocytes with a high affinity for self peptides or MHC. This eliminates cells which would direct immune responses towards self-proteins in the periphery. Negative selection is not 100% effective, some autoreactive T cells escape thymic censorship, and are released into the circulation. 

Additional mechanisms of tolerance active in the periphery exist to silence these cells such as [[anergy]], deletion, and [[regulatory T cells]]. If these [[peripheral tolerance]] mechanisms also fail, [[autoimmunity]] may arise.
