==Cancer==
Thymocytes that gain oncogenic mutations allowing uncontrolled proliferation can become thymic [[lymphomas]].

==Alternative lineages==
As well as classical αβ T cells (their development of which is outlined above), a number of other T lineages develop in the thymus, including γδ T cells and Natural Killer T (NKT)cells. Additionally, other non-T hematopoietic lineages can develop in the thymus, including B lymphocytes (B cells), Natural Killer lymphocytes (NK cells).<ref name="pmid15114674">{{cite journal |author=van den Brandt J, Voss K, Schott M, Hünig T, Wolfe MS, Reichardt HM |title=Inhibition of Notch signaling biases rat thymocyte development towards the NK cell lineage |journal=Eur. J. Immunol. |volume=34 |issue=5 |pages=1405–13 |year=2004 |month=May |pmid=15114674 |doi=10.1002/eji.200324735}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=2191276 | pmid=7504051 | volume=178 | issue=6 | title=Human natural killer cell committed thymocytes and their relation to the T cell lineage | year=1993 | month=December | author=Sánchez MJ, Spits H, Lanier LL, Phillips JH | journal=J. Exp. Med. | pages=1857–66}}</ref>), myeloid cells, and dendritic cells. However, the thymus is not a source of B, NK, or myeloid development. The development of these cells in the thymus reflects the multipotent nature of hematopoitic prognitors that seed the thymus.

